  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN149.1-kilavi">talaimakaṉ ṟaṉṉeñciṟkuc collic celavaḻuṅkiyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">How HE prevented going by speaking to his heart.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="AN149.1">
              <l><anchor n="1"/>ciṟupuṉ citalai cēṇmuyaṉ ṟeṭutta</l>
              <l>neṭuñcem puṟṟat toṭuṅkirai muṉai<del>tai</del>yi<supplied>ṟ</supplied></l>
              <l>pulvarai yiruppait toḷḷai vāṉpūp<anchor n="2"/></l>
              <l>peruṅkai <supplied>yeṇ</supplied>ki ṉiruṅkiḷai kavaru</l>
              <l>matti ṉīḷiṭaip pōki niṉṟu</l>
              <l>maritucey viḻupporu ḷeḷitiṉiṟ peṟiṉum</l>
              <l>vārēṉ vāḻiye ṉeñcē cēralar</l>
              <l>cuḷḷiyam pēriyāṟṟu veṇṇurai kalaṅka</l>
              <l>yavaṉar tanta viṇmā ṇaṉkalam</l>
              <l>poṉṉoṭu vantu kaṟiyoṭu <supplied>pe</supplied>yarum</l>
              <l>vaḷaṅkeḻu <supplied>mu</supplied>ciṟi yārppe<supplied>ḻa</supplied> vaḷai<supplied>ip</supplied></l>
              <l>peruñcamaṅ kaṭantu paṭimam vavviya</l>
              <l>neṭunal yāṉai yaṭupōrc ceḻiyaṉ</l>
              <l>koṭinuṭaṅku maṟukiṟ kūṭaṟ kuṭātu</l>
              <l>palpoṟi maññai velkoṭi yuyariya</l>
              <l>voṭiyā viḻavi <supplied>ṉe</supplied>ṭiyōṉ kuṉṟattu</l>
              <l>vaṇṭupaṭa nīṭiya kuṇṭucuṉai <supplied>nī</supplied>lat</l>
              <l>teti<supplied>r</supplied>malarp piṇaiya laṉṉaviva</l>
              <l>ḷarimatar maḻaikkaṇ ṭēṉpaṉi koḷavē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>Even if, going the long way of thorn-apple trees, (5a-c)</l>
                <l>where, when fed up with the prey contained in the tall red ant hill (2)</l>
                <l>raised with effort [visible from] the distance by the little, lowly ants, (1)</l>
                <l>the dark relatives of the large-pawed ant-eater seize (4)</l>
                <l>the tubular white flowers of the Mahua tree on the low mountain, (3)</l>
                <l>the excellent wealth ever difficult to make were to be obtained easily, (5d-6)</l>
                <l>I would not come, my heart, (7a-c)</l>
                <l>– so that the red-streaked proud rain eyes would hold sweet tears (19)</l>
                <l>of her who is like a wreath of contrasting blossoms (18)</l>
                <l>of blue lotus from the deep pool, elongated so that bees settle [there], (17)</l>
                <l>on the hill of the Tall one in unbroken festivals (16)</l>
                <l>when the many-dotted peacock is raised as a victory banner, (15)</l>
                <l>to the west of Kūṭal, with streets where flags wave, (14)</l>
                <l>of Ceḻiyaṉ, of deadly battle, with large good elephants (13)</l>
                <l>who snatched the image after besieging, so that a tumult rose,</l>
                <l>fertile Muciṟi, overcoming it in a great battle, (11f.)</l>
                <l rend="indent8">[the city] of the Cēra, (7d)</l>
                <l>where the divine, glorious, good vessels that were brought by the Yavaṉar (9)</l>
                <l>come with gold [and] return with pepper, (10)</l>
                <l>so that white foam is stirred up in the big Cuḷḷi river. (8)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>

